76877bff-1e8d-4865-a107-7d8783871d63.0a00e4ca-359c-4b4e-a01a-cfc50fff28e5.description=
This operation adds a flow variable to the local context. The variable is available in the current flow and its child flows.

Inputs\:
    keyName - The name of the flow variable to add.
    myValue - The value to assign to the flow variable.

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. It contains the value of "myValue" input field.

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.

Note\:
   If a flow variable with the same name already exists, its value will be overwritten.
76877bff-1e8d-4865-a107-7d8783871d63.689fde11-f18d-4dbb-824d-27466f1d96de.description=
This operation does not do anything. It can be used to filter flow variables by defining them as inputs and filtering them in the Results tab.

Inputs\:
    field1 – An optional input that can be used for filtering flow variables.
    field2 – An optional input that can be used for filtering flow variables.
    field3 – An optional input that can be used for filtering flow variables.
    field4 – An optional input that can be used for filtering flow variables.

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. It contains the value of  "field1" as it was specified at input or when filtered. 

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.

76877bff-1e8d-4865-a107-7d8783871d63.70faba6e-0243-449e-a0d1-602d91554384.description=
 
Check to see if the value stored in a specified flow variable, denoted by key, is null.

Inputs\:
    keyName - The key to check, i.e. the name of the flow variable. 
    trimSpaces - If set on "true" then all the whitespaces will be removed from the value stored. 
Valid values\: true, false
Default value\: false

Returns\: 
    The value in the specified key, i.e. flow variable with all whitespaces removed.

Responses\:
    isNull - If the key is a null pointer, i.e. the flow variable doesn't have an assigned value.
    notNull - If some value is stored in the key, i.e the flow variable has a value assigned. 

Notes\: 
    1. If the "trimSpaces" input is set on "true" and the value from "keyName" contains only whitespaces then the response will be "isNull". 
    2. If the "trimSpaces" input is set on "false" and the value from "keyName" contains only whitespaces then the response will be "notNull". 
    3. If any other value than "true" or "false" is passed on "trimSpaces" input then the default value (false) will be used.
76877bff-1e8d-4865-a107-7d8783871d63.c58f9a3f-eaae-4d44-96e8-98b3a49d1efe.description=Retrieves a system account username and password and stores the values as flow variables. Inputs\: accountName - The name of the system account. Starting with OO Platform version 10.20, the relative path of the system account can also be used. flowVariable - The flow variables prefix to store the system account into. The operation will receive one input with the flow variable name to assign to, but will actually assign the account to two separate variables. So if the input flowVar was "sysAcct" then two flow vars will be created "sysAcctUsername" and "sysAcctPassword". Results\: Result - A message indicating if the operation was successful or not. Responses\: success - The operation completed as stated in the description. failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully. 76877bff-1e8d-4865-a107-7d8783871d63.ce0a2d85-a72d-4677-a389-443011315c08.description=

Thiss tep will execute the SQL query and fetches the loan data. 

Inputs\:
    TNSPath- The path to the folder of the TNS file tnsnames.ora. This path must be accessible by the OO RAS service. For example, if the RAS and the Oracle server are installed on the same Windows system, the TNSPath might look like “C\:\app\Administrator\product\11.1.0\db_1\network\admin”. If the RAS and the Oracle server are on different Windows systems, you can copy the tnsnames.ora file to the RAS system, then the TNSPath might look like “C\:\Program Files\Hewlett-Packard\Operations Orchestration\RAS\Java\Default\webapp\conf” or “C\:\Temp” depending on where you place the .ora file. 
    TNSEntry - The entry name in the tnsnames.ora file that contains the connection information. The value for this input is case insensitive. For example, the value for the TNSEntry input is “TestEntry”  if the content in the tnsnames.ora file looks like the following\: 

TestEntry \=
  (DESCRIPTION \=
   (ADDRESS \= (PROTOCOL \= TCP)(HOST \= 16.110.111.111)(PORT \= 1521))
   (CONNECT_DATA \=
     (SERVER \= DEDICATED)
     (SERVICE_NAME \= orcl)
   )
 )

    Username - The username to connect to the Oracle database. 
    Password - The password for the Username.
    Command - The command to execute. 
    timeout - Seconds to wait before timing out the SQL command execution.
Default values\: 0 

Results\:
 status
 payMethod
 frequency
 nextRepaymentDate
 repaymentAmount
 cciPremium.

Responses\:
    success - Fetches the loan data
    failure - Failed to fetch loan data
